here's Dr. Chaps.

00:10:12.520 --> 00:10:15.960
Welcome back, I'm Dr. Chaps, joined now by Glenn Holloway,

00:10:15.960 --> 00:10:19.520
who is a retired colonel and author of this book,

00:10:19.520 --> 00:10:23.220
"Farming God's Way, Be the Stewards We Should Be."

00:10:24.220 --> 00:10:25.660
Colonel Holloway, welcome to the program.

00:10:25.660 --> 00:10:26.500
How are you, sir?

00:10:26.500 --> 00:10:27.340
- Oh, well, thank you for having me.

00:10:27.340 --> 00:10:29.020
It's a great opportunity.

00:10:29.020 --> 00:10:31.580
- So describe your military service

00:10:31.580 --> 00:10:33.820
and you did some civilian service after that,

00:10:33.820 --> 00:10:36.260
but now you're like all into farming.

00:10:36.260 --> 00:10:40.180
- Yeah, I started off actually back in the '70s

00:10:40.180 --> 00:10:43.260
as an enlisted Marine during the Vietnam era.

00:10:43.260 --> 00:10:45.340
And then I went back in in the '80s

00:10:45.340 --> 00:10:47.660
through Officer Candidate School at Fort Benning

00:10:47.660 --> 00:10:49.140
and got commissioned as an officer

00:10:49.140 --> 00:10:52.220
and went through as a cavalry officer, armor,

00:10:52.220 --> 00:10:55.040
and stationed in Europe and completed that

00:10:55.040 --> 00:10:57.180
as the executive officer of Allied Command Europe

00:10:57.180 --> 00:10:59.380
under NATO with Wesley Clark.

00:10:59.380 --> 00:11:02.660
And then my last civilian job was I took that knowledge

00:11:02.660 --> 00:11:04.180
and went forward and was working

00:11:04.180 --> 00:11:06.380
at the Defense Threat Reduction Agency,

00:11:06.380 --> 00:11:08.140
running the Director's Action Group,

00:11:08.140 --> 00:11:09.620
and we were in charge of monitoring

00:11:09.620 --> 00:11:12.280
and developing weapons of mass destruction.

00:11:12.280 --> 00:11:14.480
- Wow, okay.

00:11:14.480 --> 00:11:18.100
So with that great resume, you retired to go into

00:11:18.100 --> 00:11:18.700
farming.

00:11:18.700 --> 00:11:20.660
Why the switch?

00:11:20.660 --> 00:11:22.780
- Well, when I was doing all that,

00:11:22.780 --> 00:11:24.940
one of my jobs just before that one was

00:11:24.940 --> 00:11:28.180
I was chief of infrastructure,

00:11:28.180 --> 00:11:29.860
critical infrastructure for America.

00:11:29.860 --> 00:11:31.100
And I realized that food was one

00:11:31.100 --> 00:11:34.180
of our critical infrastructures that through history,

00:11:34.180 --> 00:11:36.380
if you look at what happened with Russia and the

00:11:36.380 --> 00:11:36.780
Ukraine,

00:11:36.780 --> 00:11:38.740
funny how it's kind of happening now again,

00:11:38.740 --> 00:11:40.260
they actually took control of the food

00:11:40.260 --> 00:11:41.940
and 18 million people died.

00:11:41.940 --> 00:11:44.440
So food is a critical infrastructure.

00:11:44.440 --> 00:11:46.860
And if you wanna take over a country

00:11:46.860 --> 00:11:50.280
or take control of a population, you control the food.

00:11:50.280 --> 00:11:53.340
- Can you give us a history of food production briefly?

00:11:53.340 --> 00:11:56.300
In America, it's evolved in three different stages.

00:11:56.300 --> 00:11:57.140
- Yes.

00:11:57.140 --> 00:12:00.680
Well, it started off according to the title of the book,

00:12:00.680 --> 00:12:02.020
"The Farm in God's Way."

00:12:02.020 --> 00:12:04.420
God created the earth, gave us a template

00:12:04.420 --> 00:12:06.940
on how we're supposed to grow our food,

00:12:06.940 --> 00:12:09.820
which was regenerative, word that you're hearing now,

00:12:09.820 --> 00:12:12.020
which means that every generation should have

00:12:12.020 --> 00:12:13.580
pretty much the same type of farming

00:12:13.580 --> 00:12:16.380
that regenerates the earth for the next generation.

00:12:16.380 --> 00:12:20.400
Well, back in the 19, right after World War II in the

00:12:20.400 --> 00:12:21.000
1940s,

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:23.470
there was this issue of, well, we need to feed the

00:12:23.470 --> 00:12:24.320
world.

00:12:24.320 --> 00:12:25.220
So how do we do that?

00:12:25.220 --> 00:12:26.700
We've got all these chemicals left over.

00:12:26.700 --> 00:12:30.600
So you really start seeing the advent of pesticides

00:12:30.600 --> 00:12:33.780
and herbicides and chemicals being put on the ground,

00:12:33.780 --> 00:12:36.720
which increased production with the focus

00:12:36.720 --> 00:12:38.640
of trying to feed more people.

00:12:38.640 --> 00:12:40.520
Well, they found out that didn't work real well.

00:12:40.520 --> 00:12:43.000
And so then in the late '70s,

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:44.520
we switched into what we can now call

00:12:44.520 --> 00:12:47.220
in our working energy called industrial agriculture,

00:12:47.220 --> 00:12:49.420
'cause you had the industrial revolution

00:12:49.420 --> 00:12:51.120
and all these new machineries

00:12:51.120 --> 00:12:53.520
and the ability to modify seeds

00:12:53.520 --> 00:12:55.900
and those types of things to be more productive.

00:12:55.900 --> 00:12:59.420
And so that then took over agriculture.

00:12:59.420 --> 00:13:02.520
And it sounds really good, but the problem is that

00:13:02.520 --> 00:13:05.140
to do that back in the '70s,

00:13:05.140 --> 00:13:08.420
economists, an economist by the name of John Eichert

00:13:08.420 --> 00:13:10.340
out of Missouri said, well, if you're gonna work

00:13:10.340 --> 00:13:14.020
in this production of food, bigger is better.

00:13:14.020 --> 00:13:15.500
Economy's a scale.

00:13:15.500 --> 00:13:18.620
So then we had bigger combines and we had bigger farms

00:13:18.620 --> 00:13:22.020
and all of a sudden the small farm went away

00:13:22.020 --> 00:13:24.520
and you had communities start to shrivel up.

00:13:24.520 --> 00:13:27.860
'Cause as you saw and have seen throughout the world,

00:13:27.860 --> 00:13:30.700
when the local community loses its ability

00:13:30.700 --> 00:13:32.890
to have farms or butcher the baker, the candlestick

00:13:32.890 --> 00:13:33.180
maker

